  • 0.1 We expect the sample mean to be close to population and the standev to get smaller by the ratio of one to the sample size. In this case 1/sqrt(2)
    • 0.1.1 There are 3 peaks in the density plot. You pick two people you can get MM,MF.FM,or FF. these are all equally likey so the little peak on left is all the FFs while the little peak on the right is all the MMs so the big one in the middle is both the MF and FM in the same bag so-to-speak.
    • 0.1.2 In this case the stdev was cut in half because the sample size was four. This is what the central limit theorem says. There are also 5 peaks. They go from FFFF,to FFFM, to FFMM to FMMM and finally MMMM.

Homers_data <- read.csv(file="Homers_data.csv")

my1000 <- sample(Homers_data , size = 1000, replace=T)
library(ggplot2)
sampleNumber = sample(1:10000, size = 1000)
library(dplyr)
my1000 <- Homers_data[sampleNumber, ]
names(my1000)
## [1] "sex"          "math"         "income"       "cappun"       "height"

p <- ggplot(my1000, aes(x=kkardashtemp,col=sex)) + 
  geom_density()
p

# Add mean line

0.1 We expect the sample mean to be close to population and the standev to get smaller by the ratio of one to the sample size. In this case 1/sqrt(2)

0.1.1 There are 3 peaks in the density plot. You pick two people you can get MM,MF.FM,or FF. these are all equally likey so the little peak on left is all the FFs while the little peak on the right is all the MMs so the big one in the middle is both the MF and FM in the same bag so-to-speak.

numb = 4
Hdata = Homers_data[sample(1:1000,size=numb*1000, replace=T),"kkardashtemp"]
mdata  <-matrix(Hdata,nrow=1000,ncol=numb)
x.avg <- apply(mdata,1,mean)
my1000$k4 = x.avg


p <- ggplot(my1000, aes(x=k4),col=sex) + 
  geom_density() +

# Add mean line
 geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(k4)),
            color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1)
p + ggtitle("n = 4") +
  xlab("temperature") + ylab(" density")

print(paste('mean = ', mean(my1000$k4),' sd = ',sd(my1000$k4)))
## [1] "mean =  48.33925  sd =  20.2758404670224"

0.1.2 In this case the stdev was cut in half because the sample size was four. This is what the central limit theorem says. There are also 5 peaks. They go from FFFF,to FFFM, to FFMM to FMMM and finally MMMM.

1 Now finish by adding blocks with numb being 9, then 16, 25, and 36. be sure to mention how the standard deviation progresses as the sample size changes,

numb = 9
Hdata = Homers_data[sample(1:1000,size=numb*1000, replace=T),"kkardashtemp"]
mdata  <-matrix(Hdata,nrow=1000,ncol=numb)
x.avg <- apply(mdata,1,mean)
my1000$k3 = x.avg


p <- ggplot(my1000, aes(x=k3),col=sex) + 
  geom_density() +

# Add mean line
 geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(k3)),
            color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1)
p + ggtitle("n = 9") +
  xlab("temperature") + ylab(" density")

print(paste('mean = ', mean(my1000$k3),' sd = ',sd(my1000$k3)))
## [1] "mean =  49.6458888888889  sd =  13.9634085964525"

Take the standard deviation and put in the data that is from the central limit. the standard deviation shrinks as the number gets higher example 4 divided by 2, 9 is divided by 3. 16 divided by 4 and son on. The standard deviation r not. The expected value is the mean will always stay the same and the standard deviation will always shrink. This numb is a demonstration of what happens. r sd(my1000\(k3)' we expect 14 and we get 'r sd(my1000\)k3)

numb = 16
Hdata = Homers_data[sample(1:1000,size=numb*1000, replace=T),"kkardashtemp"]
mdata  <-matrix(Hdata,nrow=1000,ncol=numb)
x.avg <- apply(mdata,1,mean)
my1000$k4 = x.avg


p <- ggplot(my1000, aes(x=k4),col=sex) + 
  geom_density() +

# Add mean line
 geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(k4)),
            color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1)
p + ggtitle("n = 16") +
  xlab("temperature") + ylab(" density")

print(paste('mean = ', mean(my1000$k4),' sd = ',sd(my1000$k4)))
## [1] "mean =  49.5893125  sd =  10.6437439474469"

the standard deviation is now a quarter of what it was before which now it is 10. We expect 7 and we got r sd(my1000$k4)
